    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "t_start": 0.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "A student writes ell-squared for the angular momentum eigenvalue. Spectroscopy says the answer is ell times ell plus one. The plus one cannot be removed.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "Why Quantum Mechanics\nNeeds ell(ell+1), Not ell squared",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.64,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "t_start": 7.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Angular momentum squared should equal the square of its maximum z-component. Maximum z is ell h-bar. So the eigenvalue should be ell-squared h-bar-squared. Every formula says ell times ell-plus-one h-bar-squared instead.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "Create"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.49,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "t_start": 17.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Angular momentum squared should equal its maximum z-component squared. Every formula says otherwise, with a plus-one that cannot be removed. Why?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION",
        "headline": "L squared should equal L-z max squared. Every measurement gives ell(ell+1), not ell squared. The plus-one cannot be dropped. Why does L squared give more than the square of L-z?",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.27,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "t_start": 26.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Think of a ladder of m-values, running from negative ell to positive ell in integer steps. The top rung is m equals ell. L-z on the top rung gives ell h-bar. So L-z-max-squared gives ell-squared h-bar-squared.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "Create"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.61,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "t_start": 37.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "But L-squared is not just L-z-squared. It is L-x-squared plus L-y-squared plus L-z-squared. The x and y components are never exactly zero. They contribute.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.93,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "t_start": 47.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "So where does the extra contribution come from exactly?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE MECHANISM",
        "headline": "The commutator\ncreates the extra term",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.0,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "t_start": 54.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 14,
      "narration_text": "Write L-squared using the lowering times raising operator. Expand that product. The commutator between them \u2014 L-minus times L-plus \u2014 produces an extra minus h-bar times L-z. That cross-term is the plus-one. It comes directly from the non-commutativity of the angular momentum components.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 20.19,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "t_start": 68.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "The ladder must have a top rung \u2014 you cannot climb forever.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE MECHANISM",
        "headline": "The top rung condition\nforces the plus-one",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.19,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "t_start": 75.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "At the top rung, the raising operator annihilates the state. That condition sets the eigenvalue. Solving it gives lambda equals ell times ell-plus-one h-bar-squared \u2014 the exact formula. The plus one is the commutator's signature.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.23,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "t_start": 87.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "This means the total angular momentum always exceeds its z-component. The vector can never align perfectly with any axis. That is not a measurement limitation \u2014 it is a geometric consequence of the algebra.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "This means the total angular momentum always exceeds its z-component. The\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B10.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.72,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "t_start": 96.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Every spectral line in every atom traces back to this one extra term. The plus-one is not a correction. It is the structure.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.84,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B11.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B11.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "t_start": 104.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "A worked example.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE EXAMPLE",
        "headline": "The d-orbital: ell = 2",
        "dek": "(illustrative)"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 1.2,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B12.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B12.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "t_start": 111.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 18,
      "narration_text": "For ell equals 2, the naive guess gives L-squared equals 4 h-bar-squared. Spectroscopy gives 6 h-bar-squared \u2014 ell times ell-plus-one is 2 times 3. The extra 2 h-bar-squared is exactly the commutator cross-term. Five m-values exist: minus 2, minus 1, zero, 1, 2. None of them, alone, accounts for the total.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B13.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 23.01,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B13.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B13.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B14",
      "t_start": 129.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "L squared gives more than L-z max squared because the components do not commute. Non-commutativity forces the extra term. The plus-one is not a correction \u2014 it is the commutator counted.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "L squared = ell(ell+1), not ell squared. The extra term is the commutator made visible.",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B14.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.749,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/clips/B14.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-ell/mp3/beat-B14.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "NBB01",
      "act": "VERDICT",
      "title": "Liam verdict \u2014 ClaudeVerdictArtifact",
      "engine": "kokoro",
      "voice": "am_onyx",
      "narration_text": "Here's what the body just demonstrated. For ell equals 2, the naive guess gives L-squared equals 4 h-bar-squared. Spectroscopy gives 6 h-bar-squared \u2014 ell times ell-plus-one is 2 times 3. The extra 2 h-bar-squared is exactly the commutator cross-term. Five m-values exist: minus 2, minus 1, zero, 1, 2. None of them, alone, accounts for the total. L squared gives more than L-z max squared because the components do not commute. Non-commutativity forces the extra term. The plus-one is not a correction \u2014 it is the commutator counted.",
